@DaniBet Here is how I do it with a little commentary around it.

In Podman, communication between Pods (disregarding containers here because the kube functions are always pods) can be done through a CNI plugin called `dnsname`.  However, dnsname is not enabled on the default Podman network (following docker's lead here).  This is further complicated by the fact that play kube will always use the default Podman network.

Before making the changes below, make sure your pods and rm'd.

So we simply need to enable dnsname on Podman's default network. Here is a diff:
```
--- /etc/cni/net.d/87-podman-bridge.conflist.orig	2021-02-08 09:16:25.263128042 -0600
+++ /etc/cni/net.d/87-podman-bridge.conflist	2021-02-08 09:17:09.382033868 -0600
@@ -32,6 +32,13 @@
     },
     {
       "type": "tuning"
-    }
+    },
+      {
+         "type": "dnsname",
+         "domainName": "dns.podman",
+         "capabilities": {
+            "aliases": true
+         }
+      }
   ]
 }

```
**Note:** Be sure to add a trailing comma (`,`) to the tuning stanza.  You can also pipe the file through something like `jq` to make sure your JSON is valid.

Your pods should now be able to resolve each other by name.

